{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_krum_ver01/data/sn86090238/00517175584/1911012901/0613.xml":{"full_text":"Diaarnin iltue\niratiux tlie rate ut\n'ncr\u00bb-a>lni< pres\nsure la owaa\u2019t\ndepth*. A direr\ncan only reach 200\nfeet. The electric\neye can dcacend\nmany wUea-\nA RUSSIAN scientist has Invented an artificial\neye which will enable man to peer into every\npart of th* earth that has hitherto been hidden\nfrom him.\nThe Inventor is Professor J. H. Rosing, who holds the\nchair of physics In the Nicholas I. Institute of Tech\nnology at St Petersburg.\nThe Invention is made possible by the recently dis\ncovered Cathode rays, which are influenced and set in\nmotion by the Impulse of an electric current The\nobject to be looked at impresses itself on a rotating\nmirror at one end of the line, is transformed Into elec\ntricity and reproduces Itself at the other end by means\nof the Cathode rays acting on a fluorescent screen.\nThis wonderful apparatus can be dropped down to\nthe darkest depths of the ocean. Into the heart of a\nfiery volcano or the stomach of a sick person and\nwill then enable the observer, sitting at ease any dis\ntance away, to observe what is \"olng on In those\nstrange places. It sees as well In the darkness as In\nthe light\nIt Is evident that It will be particularly useful In\ninvestigating the ocean bed at great depths. We have\nonly a very vague -knowledge of the creatures that\nlive in those abysmal depths, and our Ideas of the\nscenery there are purely imaginative.\nThe fish that are brought up from a great depth\nburst to pieces on reaching the surface. because they\nhave been accustomed to exist under a tremendous\npressure. There Is little doubt that there are many\nmonsters living there of which we have no conception.\nThe mystery concerning the ocean depths gave the\nclever scientific romancer, H. G. Wells, material for\none of his most exciting stories. He Imagined that a\nvast unfathomable gorge existing in the middle of the\nAtlantic Ocean was peopled by semi-human creatures.\nMan has evolved from fish ancestors. Why should not\nsome other fish have evolved amid sheltered and\nfavorable surroundings into a higher type, while still\nremaining beneath the waters?\nWells's hero, a daring young scientist, believed there\nwere such creatures and Invented a machine with\nwhich to visit them. It was a globe, indestructible by\nthe pressure of the water, which sank automatically\nto the bottom, and rose at the will of the In\nventor. He was treated as a god by the queer ocean\npeople, whose fine had grown into feet, but on a sec\nond trip his machine failed to come back, and he\nstayed below and died.\nProfessor Rorlng has made possible the most Im\nportant part of Well*'* story, namely, to see what is\ngoing on at the greatest ocean depths.\nThere are great areas of the ocean bottom six or\nseven miles\u2014or 36,900 feet\u2014deep. Now, the greatest\ndepth to which a diver has ever been was stated re\ncently to be 198 feet. Even that was very extraor\ndinary, and hardly any man could endure It. Below\nthat the pressure becomes unendurable. First the\nwould-be explorer would be hold helpless and immov\nable, and a little further down he would be crushed\nto death.\nIt Is evident that man has hardly seen beyond the\nsurface of the ocean. The depth to which he can see\nwith the Rosing apparatus is only limited by the length\nof wire that can be made.\nA very different, and per.u-ps more Important field\noi usefulness for this machine will He In exploring\nthe interior of the human body. Many of the deadly\ndiseases reach a fatal stage because the physician\ncannot see the interior of the body. Of course, many\nhitherto concealed parte of the body have been brought\nto light by modern surgery, but there are still dis\nadvantages about this method of viewing the interior.\nWith the Rosing electric eye the physician can view\nthe throat, stomach and whole intestinal system of his\npatient without doing him any injury. The physician\nwill be able to view the scene with clearness and de\nliberation. This will mean entirely new light on the\nprocess of life -\\nd disease.\nThe apparatus will also be very useful In exploring\nthe interior of volcanoes, about which, tor Obvious\nreasons, we know little.\nCountless other uses for t is remarkable invention\nwill at once suggest thl?\" j:elves. When there has been\nSCIENCES NEWEST WONDER\nHow the Electric Eye Works.\nThe Image of What It Sees la Ihe\nStomach la Carried Vp the Wires\nThrough the Gullet aad la\nReflected by the Receiv\ning Meehan In tn L'poa\nthe Disk Before\nthe Phyalclaa.\nIL Fish Which Lives a Mile Deep\nin the Ocean and Carries a\nPressure of a Ton to the\nSquare Inch Man\nFinds 45 Pounds\nUncomfortable.\nan accident in a coal mine, the electric eye ca 4 be\ndropped into hidden corners to look for bodies, and\npossible survivors. It will no longer be necessary for\nbrave rescuers to lose their liver by venturing need\nlessly into the poisonous gases.\nIn war, as well as In peace, In exploration, in In\ndustry and in science, electric eye promises great\nusefulness.\nProfessor Rosing has written a description of his\n(Continued from Preceding Pa*e\u00ab)\ning form to the simple articles of do\nmestic which be constructed.\nMany of these objects, thousands \u00bbf\nyears old, are so well designed that\nthey delight the eye of the art\ndealer to-day.\nSome of the most interesting dis\ncoveries in prehistoric art have\nbeen made in South America, where\nextinct and forgotten races have\nleft extensive ruins of all kinds.\nThe British Museum has jUst ac\nqulred from Hewitt Meyring, the ex\nplorer, a large collection of pottery\nmade by the ancient Clmus of Peru.\nIt is estimated that these vessels\nCopyright, I*ll. by\u2018Amerlcan-Examlner. Great Britain Rights Reserved.\nTHE EARLIEST ART OF MAN.\nThe English\nWriter, H. G.\nWells\u2019s Fantastic\nIdea of the\nMan-Like Fish\nThat Live in\nthe 4-Mile Deep\nChasm of the\nAtlantic\u2014and\nWhich the\nElectric Eye\nMay or May\nNot Re\ndiscover.\nThat the year 1910 must have been a\nreasonably prosperous one in the\nUnited States is Indicated by the\nfigures of importation of the class of arti\ncles usually termed \u2018'luxuries.\u2019\u2019\nNo more satisfactory barometer of gen\neral business conditions Is found than the\nfigures representing the Importation of\narticles purely or chiefly luxuries, includ\ning diamonds and other precious stones,\nlaces, art works, wines, tobacco and manu\nfactures thereof, and other articles of this\ncharacter.\nThis is Illustrated by 1 K'ance at the\nyearly record of Imports is recorded by\nthe Bureau of Statistics of the Department\nof Commerce and Labor.\nare over 7,000 years old. They are\nwell made, and of attractive form.\nSome of them are decorated with\nhuman figures, which show that the\nmen of those times were as fond of\nelaborate bonnets as the women of\nto-day.\nThe more investigators dive Into\nthe record* of the past the more they\nare impressed with the antiquity of\ncivilization. It seems impossible to\ndiscover a period of human society\nwhen men did not possess a consid\nerable degree of skill.\nThe men of the Old Stone Age,\nwhich was Immeasurably before the\ndawn of any recorded history,\ncarved their flints in a very Intelli\ngent manner. With the horn and\nANELECTRIC EYE\nDropped Into Your\nStomach It Shows What\nIs Wrong\u2014Dropped\nInto the Sea It Reveals\nthe Secrets of Its\nDepths\u2014Dropped Into\nVolcanoes It Bares\nthe Mystery of Their\nDeepest Pits\u2014\nJust As Though Your\nOwn Two Eyes*\nWere There!\ninvention. He says that It is an electric telescope, and\nconsists of two sections or stations connected by elec\ntric wires. In the ordinary telescope there is but one\nactive station the receiver, or great lens, which draws\nthe object to be studied near by Its power of mag\nnification. In the electric telescope, which operates\nbetween any two points to which the sending end can\nbe dispatched, the picture as seen at that transmitting\nend is made visible at the receiving station. All that\ncrosses the field of vlslor at the sending station must\nbe transferred to the receiving station, and repro\nduced there. In order to do this pictures are sent\nat the rate of <ot less than forty per second, and\nthese are reproduced at the receiving end of the wire.\nThe great problem before the inventor was to de\nvise apparatus which would get all of the pictures\nwithin the range of vision, and transfer them over the\nwires from the sending to the receiving station. In\norder to do this Professor Rosing placed at the send\ning station a device by which the sensitive screen was\nmade to revolve over the entire field of vision in one\nsecond., He has succeeded, by dividing the whole pic\nture into reflected sections of light, which are trans\nformed into electricity and transmitted to the receiv\ning station.\nUpon arrival a specially designed apparatus ro\ncelves the impulses, reverses the operation of the send\ning station, and reflects upon a screen, or upon the\nLuxuries That Are Prosperity Barometers.\nbone of the reindeer they made\nknives, lance heads, arrows and\nneedles, not only with skill but with\nartistic taste.\nCompared with these prehistoric\nmen the savages of to-day appear to\nbe rather degenerates than men in\nan early stage of development\nOn the preceding page you see\nsome examples of the very earliest\nart of man, but a long period of de\nvelopment must have preceded It\nWe are far from possessing any\nadequate record of the time when\nh-man intelligence was at its very\ndawn, when the mind of man was\nscarcely beyond that of the beast\nHere Is one of the great puzzles of\narchaeology.\nA Fish\nWhich Lives\nComfortably\nat a Half\nMile Depth and\nCarries an\nElectric Eye of\nits Own\nBetween its Two\nOthers.\nA Photograph\nof a Cavern\n2,000 Feet Down\nin Mt. Etna,\nTaken by the\nElectric Eye.\nIn years of marked depression. 1894 and\n1895, for example, the value of diamonds\nand other precious stones imported\ndropped from $16,000,000 in 1893 to $5,-\n500,000 In 1894, $7,500,000 In 1895, and\nabout $6,750,000 In 1896; gradually moving\nupward again until 1899 and MOD and\nreaching a total of $32,000,000 In 1903 and\n$42,000,000 In 1907. In the fiscal year\n1908, a year of business depression, the\ntotal fell to $16,750,000, returning to $29,-\n000,000 in 1909 and $48,000,000 in the fiscal\nyear 1910, while the figures of the \u2666cal\nendar year will not materially differ from\nthose of the flscal year.\nThe figures of diamond importation\nabove cited are merely an example of the\nevidences of prosperity supplied by the\nfigures of Imports. In auto\nmobiles, art works, laces,\nfeathers, furs, wines and\nliquors, tobacco, decorated\nchinaware and numerous other\narticles named in the list of\nImportations, the figures of\n1910 are large, and the Impor\ntation of articles usually\nclassed as \"luxuries\u201d will show\na total of between two hun\ndred and three hundred million\ndollars\u2019 value.\nOf laces and embroideries\nalone the value Imported dur\ning the year just ended approx\nimated $45,000,000, a very large\nproportion of which was cotton-\nThis class of Importations also\nshows considerable fluctuations\naccording to conditions of pros\nperity or otherwise, though\nLife at a Two Mile Ocean Depth\n\u2014Which the Electric Eye\nEnables Man to Watch.\neye of the observer the e~act picture of whatevei\ncrossed the field of vision at the sending station.\nEverything depends upon the transmission of th*\noscillations of the lighted field of vision, with all its\nvariations, from the brightest light to the deepest\nshadow, and this must be done in a fraction of time,\nsometimes a millionth of a second. This difficulty has\nprevented the success of previous attempts. It is Ina\npossible with simple mechanical aids like mirrors. It\nwas necessary to secure some agent that would be af\nfected at once by the variations in the luminous field\nand by electric currents.\nThe Professor knew by experiment that besides or\ndinary light rays there are others, which, while possess\ning all the characteristics of luminous rays, are affected\nby oscillating motions une\u2019er the influence of some\nexternal electric or magnetic force. These are the\nCathode rays, which are produced in a vacuum almost\nas quickly as light, and which, when projected upon the\nbody, create an intensely bright light This agent was\nemployed at the receiving station. The Cathode ray\nIs easily influenced by the slightest oscillation of the\nelectric current.\nWhen we add to the rotating mirrors at the sending\nstation, which form the moving portion of the optic\nsystem In this apparatus, some small dynamos, and\nguide the currents at the receiving station by electro\nmagnets, placed near a Crookes tube (In which Ca\nthode rays are generated), these currents make the\nCathode rays oscillate in absolute correspondence with\nthe movement of the optic axis at the sending station.\nThe Cathode rays project themselves on the fluores\ncent screen placed In the same Crookes tube. They\ncause a fluorescence at the point of incidence and\ntrace a luminous zigzag line corresponding to that\nwhich the receiving eye makes in the field of vision\nwhich it follows.\nThe rapidity of this movement causes the separat*\nzigzags of this line to blur into a single lumlnoui\nsquare in the eye.\nNow, in order to produce tn this square some Imagi\ncorresponding to the field of vision. It Is necessary\nthat the Cathode rays shall only fall on the screen\nat the moment when the recelvei meets a luminous\npoint on the visual field At other times the rays must\nbe masked.\napparatus at the transmitter ac\ncomplishes this. The Cathode rays remain ordinarily\nhidden behind the diaphragm placed In it* way and\nit I* only at the moment when the light is thrown on\nthe photo-electrip apparatus taat the electric current\nwhich it at the receiving point begin*\nto exert its effect on the rays and forces them to pas*\nthrough the diaphragm and impress themselves on the\nscreen.\nnot as great a* diamonds.\nThe value of cotton laces, embroideries\netc,. Imported In the flscal year 1893 wm\nand dropped ln ,804 ,0 \u00abB.ooo*\n000. Again in the period of 1907-8 depressloi\nthe value of importations of this da*,\ndropped from $39,750,000 in the flscal veai\n1907 to $33,750,000 In IMfI.reS.JT\n$34 333,333 in 1909 and $36,750,000\u2122 1910\nin art,Cles of ,m P\u00b0rtatior\nIn 1910 which are usually classed as\nluxuries are: Silk laces. $4,500,000- laces\nof flax and other similar fibres. $4.000 000-\ntobacco, cigars, etc.. $33,000,000; furs and\n-ur skins, $25,000,000; art works $2lOOO\n000; spirits, wines and liquors $2O 000 i\n000; feathers and flowers, naturai and aril\nflcial, \u00bbH,0(\u00bb000; toys, $8,000,000; mi\nhogany, $3,500,000; jewelry, $2,000 000-\nmanufactures of gold and silver s\u2018>ooo.\n000; and beads and ornament*/perfumer\nles, cosmetics, shells, orchids. p%e* \u201cnd\nsmokers' articles. and musical i D it\"umen%\nMSSV\u2122'- Ww 1000 M0\nmanufactures, Europe; m the case of to\nbacco. mahogany, and other article\u00ae nt\nthis class, the tropical sections; while\nthe twenty-five million dollar.' worth of\nfurs and fur skins originate largely of\ncourse, in the frigid or seml-frlgld section*\nof world Moat the imported laces\nwhether of cotton, flax, or silk, are mart\nin Switzerland, Franco. Germany Belgium\nEngland and Ireland; most of the tobacco\nand cigar* come from Cuba: most of the\nart work* from various European coun\ntries, and most of the toys from Germany","height":"26740","width":"20352"}}
